# v0.5.0 — 2026-06-11 — benoitcayladbx

## Feature: Domain access roster on the Validation page

**Context**: Requested a new section on the Domain → Validation (review) page,
placed below the "Consistency checks" card, listing the people and groups who
have a role on the loaded domain (Viewer / Editor / Builder) with their role
made explicit. The page already surfaced the lifecycle, a consistency summary
and the audit trail; reviewers had no in-context way to see *who* can view,
edit or build the domain. Domain roles live in the per-domain registry
permissions (`.domain_permissions.json`); the existing
`/settings/domain-permissions/{domain}` endpoint is admin-only (for editing),
so a read-only, member-visible surface was added on the review router instead.

**Changes**:
1. `src/back/objects/registry/ReviewService.py` — added a `review_team(request,
   session_mgr, settings, folder)` static method. It resolves the Databricks
   host/token and registry config from the loaded domain (same pattern as
   `_resolve_roles`), reads the per-domain entries via
   `permission_service.list_domain_entries(...)`, keeps only the assignable
   roles (viewer / editor / builder), and returns
   `{success, domain, members:[{principal, principal_type, display_name,
   role}]}` sorted most-privileged first then by display name. Imports
   `ASSIGNABLE_ROLES` from `PermissionService`.
2. `src/api/routers/internal/review.py` — added `GET /review/{folder}/{version}/team`
   delegating to `ReviewService.review_team`. The `version` path segment is kept
   for URL symmetry with the sibling review endpoints (the access list is
   per-domain, not per-version) and is dropped in the handler.
3. `src/front/static/domain/js/domain-review.js` — added a "Domain access" card
   (`teamCard()`) rendered in the left column directly below the Consistency
   checks card, and `loadTeam()` which fetches the new endpoint and renders the
   members grouped by role (Builder → Editor → Viewer). Each group shows a
   role badge + short description (Builder: "Can edit, build and publish";
   Editor: "Can edit the model"; Viewer: "Read-only access") and member chips
   reuse the existing `review-person` / `review-avatar` styles (group principals
   get a people-fill avatar). Empty state explains only admins can access the
   domain. `loadTeam()` is invoked from `loadReview()` after `render()`.
4. `src/front/static/domain/css/domain-review.css` — added `.review-avatar-group`
   (muted avatar for group principals) and small `.review-role-group` /
   `.review-role-head` spacing rules.
5. `tests/units/registry/test_review_service.py` — added 4 tests for
   `review_team`: role/name sort order, filtering out non-assignable roles
   (e.g. admin), display-name defaulting to the principal for groups, and the
   empty-folder `ValidationError`.
6. `tests/units/api/test_review_endpoints.py` — added `test_team_delegates_to_service`
   asserting the endpoint forwards the folder and drops the version.

**Modified files**:
- `src/back/objects/registry/ReviewService.py`
- `src/api/routers/internal/review.py`
- `src/front/static/domain/js/domain-review.js`
- `src/front/static/domain/css/domain-review.css`
- `tests/units/registry/test_review_service.py`
- `tests/units/api/test_review_endpoints.py`

**Test result**: `pytest tests/units/registry/test_review_service.py
tests/units/api/test_review_endpoints.py` → **60 passed**. Full-suite
`pytest --ignore=tests/property` → 2752 passed, 53 skipped, 19 failed; the 19
failures are pre-existing full-run async-harness issues (every async test in
`test_review_endpoints` and the whole `test_set_version_status_endpoint`,
including untouched tests like `test_my_tasks_delegates`, plus dtwin/home/
navigation e2e) — all 60 of the touched tests pass cleanly when the files are
run in isolation. `tests/property` skipped (`hypothesis` not installed in this
env). No new lint errors on the edited files.

## Fix: Domain access roster now shares the Teams matrix source

**Context**: Locally the new "Domain access" roster listed several principals
that the Registry → Teams page did not show. Root cause: the Teams matrix
(`build_teams_matrix_result`) renders one row per **Databricks App principal**
(`list_app_principals`) and overlays the per-domain role onto those rows, so a
`.domain_permissions.json` entry whose principal is no longer in the App ACL
(an orphan assignment, common in local/test data) is invisible there. The first
cut of `review_team` instead listed the **raw** `.domain_permissions.json`
entries, so those orphans surfaced — making the two views disagree.

**Changes**:
1. `src/back/objects/registry/ReviewService.py` — `review_team` now builds the
   roster from the **same source as the Teams matrix**: it fetches the App
   principals (`permission_service.list_app_principals`) and the per-domain
   entries (`list_domain_entries`), then emits a member only when an App
   principal (user by email, group by name) has an assignable role on the
   domain. This is exactly the "filled cells" of the domain's column in the
   Teams matrix, so the Validation roster and the Teams page are now
   guaranteed consistent. Orphan permission entries are no longer shown.
2. `tests/units/registry/test_review_service.py` — reworked the `review_team`
   tests to mock both the App ACL and the per-domain entries; added
   `test_review_team_excludes_entries_without_app_principal` (the exact
   regression) and `test_review_team_includes_groups`.

**Modified files**:
- `src/back/objects/registry/ReviewService.py`
- `tests/units/registry/test_review_service.py`

**Test result**: `pytest tests/units/registry/test_review_service.py
tests/units/api/test_review_endpoints.py` → **61 passed**. No new lint errors.

## Polish: Ontology Designer detail-panel resize handle

**Context**: On the Ontology page, the right-side detail panel (entity /
relationship editor) is resizable via a draggable left border. The handle was
an 8px white strip with thin left + right borders and a small 40px grey nub
floating in the middle — the divider line had no clean top/bottom termination
and the grip looked unfinished. Requested a more beautiful treatment.

**Changes**:
1. `src/front/static/ontology/css/ontology-shared-panels.css` —
   `.detail-panel-resize-handle` reworked: transparent 11px hit area with a
   full-height hairline divider drawn via `::before` (top:0 / bottom:0), so the
   border now has clean top & bottom ends spanning the whole panel. On
   hover/active the divider thickens to 2px and turns brand-primary. The grip
   `.resize-bar` became a rounded pill (5px wide, `border-radius:999px`) with a
   soft drop shadow that grows (46px → 64px) and turns primary on hover/active.
   Removed the now-redundant `border-left` on `.shared-detail-panel` to avoid a
   double line next to the handle's divider.

**Modified files**:
- `src/front/static/ontology/css/ontology-shared-panels.css`

**Test result**: CSS-only change (no Python touched). No new lint errors on the
edited file.

